AI is a loudspeaker üì£  Automation adds speed üèÉ‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è

If the data you‚Äôre feeding is already noisy, both will just amplify that noise.

So how do we get more precise?

We've known ‚Äúgarbage in, garbage out‚Äù for long enough to know better. And now that AI and daily automations have fully entered the mix, the noise gets turned way up when we are using the wrong data. 

I see so many exceptional revenue leaders drowning in data overload, stressed about showing up to the Board or Leadership meeting with metrics that don‚Äôt move results.  They tell 'a' story... but 'what' story are you trying to tell with this data?  Let alone, understand... 

üôå This is where my coaching experience (1) makes sense, and (2), shines! ‚ú®  It's where Tableau helped me re-invent my career in tech and learn to tell better stories by understanding, measuring, and using, better data. Whether it‚Äôs a simple cartwheel, an elite pole vaulter or a SaaS sales squad, the fix is often the same: Strip it back to the basics. Get laser-focused.

Before me or my team touches any automation or AI, I run every project through a simple filter...my own kind of BS detector for myself.  We strip ideas down to no more than 5 core data points to force clarity. That‚Äôs it, and, I keep a few ground rules handy.

‚òù One clear sentence. If you can‚Äôt say the project‚Äôs goal in one clear sentence, you‚Äôre not ready to build the dashboard. End of story.
‚úå Each datapoint has to tell its own clear story.  If it doesn‚Äôt, test if it can form a meaningful rate or ratio. If it still can‚Äôt, it‚Äôs gone.
ü§ü Every datapoint must drive a decision or action. If no one can answer ‚ÄúWhat would we do differently if this number changed?‚Äù it doesn‚Äôt belong on the dashboard. Let every metric earn it's place by influencing a decision.
üññ Measure the controllables, not the distractions. Keep your focus on the inputs your team can execute, not vanity outcomes.

Starting with a sharp focus helps your teams align quicker as your whole revenue machine begins to run with new-found confidence üí™

If you're up for the clean up, take a hard look at your dashboards today, and get honest. How many of those metrics really deserve to stay?

In 2026, let's ditch volume and lead with precision. üéØ


#DataDiscipline #Leadership #AI
#SalesLeadership #RevenueEnablement

‚ú®Precision. Practice. Patience.‚ú®
It‚Äôs how athletes, and revenue teams, win.

I‚Äôve been COACHING for 25 years (yes, I started at age 3! üòâ)

Coaching allows me to experienceüí°lightbulb moments, as I chase the thrill of growth with those I coach! So what‚Äôs the process‚Ä¶? 

It‚Äôs kind of the same for athletes as it is for revenue teams I‚Äôve coached. Check it out‚Ä¶

ü•áBe a student of your craft. Know what BEST looks like. And I suppose, what good, great, and awful look like too.

ü•àCompare each effort to what you know is best-in-class. Use tools to analyze. Measure competency. Find  gaps. Develop fundamentals. Design drills, aka ‚Äúmicro-learnings.‚Äù

ü•âCreate a plan to transfer knowledge. Set up a disciplined, albeit flexible, training program with these repetitive micro-learnings. 

üèÖCommit together. Re-evaluate & shift continuously and consciously.

üèÜ This is a recipe for greatness! ü§©

I could SO easily make the comparison to gymnastics, my first true love. Learning the fundamentals through a gymnasts‚Äô skill set  helped me create a process to perfect coaching at the highest levels across many sports.

I‚Äôve worked with, and alongside, national and world champions across multiple sports - as well as - former, current and future Olympians in gymnastics, soccer, and track & field‚Ä¶ namely Pole Vault. (No emoji for that?!)

‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî

This photo is from the Olympic Training Center, where Stacy Dragila, OLY, the first female Olympic gold medal winner in Women‚Äôs Pole Vault invited me to share my formula for success in the form of ‚Äúmicro-learnings‚Äù for her athletes: Gymnastics for pole vaulters. ü§∏‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏èü§∏ü§∏‚Äç‚ôÇÔ∏è

I spent numerous summers with her teaching fundamentals of body positions and 3 key skills. 

Stacy recognized that my ability to define GREAT in just 3 fundamental skills, was transformative for her crew. She invited me to coach alongside her because she knew the difference between a premature arch and winning would come down to knowing the fundamentals, and breaking big attempts into coachable moments fixed that!

I was hired to show vaulters what to do, and I didn‚Äôt just show training videos to communicate what the best in the world do. 

I absolutely did not tell athletes to just, ‚Äútry harder.‚Äù

I moved closer. Found the tiny misalignments. Broke imperfections down into micro-learnings through simple, effective drills.

I helped her vaulters build confidence one micro-win at a time until they could hit each body position at full speed, rising up a freakishly bendy pole, while navigating changing gravitational planes, with absolute authority in the air.

Sales enablement is the exact same craft. Our  pipelines are the event we get to drive greatness from. We analyze technique, spot the gaps, design targeted practice & stay out on the track with our teams until the skill is truly theirs.

‚ú®Precision. Practice. Patience.‚ú®
That‚Äôs how athletes, and revenue teams, win.

What is the high-flying skill in your sales motion that needs breaking down? Let‚Äôs talk.

As a VP of Revenue, I experimented with grounding GTM efforts in a strong enablement mindset.  Alongside my team, we created a playbook that sent revenue soaring.

Here‚Äôs a walk-through of the key enablement strategies that fueled our hard-won, doubling of revenue in 2025.

(I know the superstitions say it‚Äôs too early to call, but that‚Äôs the confidence I have!)

üïµÔ∏è‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏èFind Your ICP and Focus!  We used SPICED by Winning by Design to systematically develop our ICP, ensuring every rep knew exactly who to target on every call.  This focus helped us prioritize quality > quantity, and helped our talented team fish in the best fishing holes üêãüêü

üóûÔ∏èMaster the Messaging with practice.  Training isn‚Äôt a calendar event, it‚Äôs a discipline.  Role play and live-call shadowing became central to our sales culture.  Through a disciplined practice cadence combined with continuous real-call exposure (cameras on!), our reps became experts at uncovering deeper pain points and seamlessly positioning our solution. It‚Äôs been a minute since I last posted, and I‚Äôve been reflecting on a question I ponder too often, why is Revenue Enablement still the secret weapon for high-performing revenue teams?  And when is the right time for companies to invest?

I'm curious... is enablement only effective when laser-focused on driving revenue?  Or are there other approaches sales leaders are using to spark early success?

I‚Äôve had hundreds of conversations around this, attended and spoken at events, consulted on revenue teams, and even experimented with my own career path. (Not the most fun thing I've done, fwiw.)

Time after time, I see one clear trend stand out (and it‚Äôs backed by the amazing frameworks of SiriusDecisions'): Companies that invest early in enablement typically see aligned messaging, faster ramp times, and measurable revenue lift within the first year.

Zoom in on that last part, "measurable revenue lift!"  Isn't that the stuff my friends? 

Because are we really slaving over aligned messaging and faster ramp times if it's not contributing to... ahem, measurable revenue lift?

We're not. 

We know Enablement builds cross-functional alignment, clarity, sometimes inspiration, and if it's good, then also a culture of continuous learning, which every go-to-market team needs as it takes shape.

But do we all agree on the #1 driving focus of enablement?  Can we please agree that our purpose is to drive revenue? (Please? ü§™)

With just over a year poured into my VP role, I have never been more certain that startups who prioritize enablement early will build a foundation for sustainable success.

So here‚Äôs my question for you:

When did your organization begin to prioritize enablement?  Did you use your current team, or make a dedicated hire?  If you could do it again, would you bring them in sooner?

Phil Putnam & Shannon S., I would really love to hear from you both on this. (Also, San Diego misses us!) üå¥ üíñ 

üì∏  Pictured with Nimisha Mahuvakar & Gaurav Mishra of Proshort, a team who knows how to use principles of Enablement to drive revenue.

data.text:
Today marks a milestone that redefined my path.

365 days ago, corporate America taught me a hard lesson.

Despite the revenue I'd generated, the relationships I'd built, and the impact I'd made, I was laid off.

The aftermath was raw:
‚Ä¢ My kids witnessed my vulnerability
‚Ä¢ As the primary breadwinner, I faced the weight of financial uncertainty
‚Ä¢ I had to fight for basic unemployment benefits
‚Ä¢ Every belief I'd held about career security was questioned

But in that darkness, critical questions emerged: Why was I pouring my energy into someone else's vision? What dreams had I set aside in pursuit of "stability"? What would it look like to build something truly mine?

365 days ago was the last time someone else decided my fate.

The journey hasn't been easy. We stripped our lives down to the essentials. We made hard choices about our finances - decisions that tested our resolve daily.

Looking back, being laid off wasn't just an ending. It was the push I needed to discover my path. Ok - maybe the swift kick ü¶µ

To anyone navigating a similar storm: Your story isn't over.

Sometimes our biggest setbacks clear the way for our greatest comebacks.

In the past year, I have:
- done work that has impact and makes my heart sing
- leaned into networking, building my personal brand, and making lifelong friendships with people I met, here, on Linkedin
- joined organizations that gave me opportunities to speak, plan retreats, advise

I am thankful ‚ù§Ô∏è. I‚Äôm just getting started ‚Äî Here‚Äôs to the path ahead.

If someone had told me a year ago that I would be able to do what I did yesterday I would have thought they were insane.

I had an in-person meeting with a prospect which RARELY happens these days for me.

I had a few discovery calls previously with my Champion and this was a chance for me to meet the rest of the decision making team, including the CEO. 

As usual, I had a jam packed day and didn't have a tone of time to prep for the meeting before I had to jump in the car. 

So, I decided to put some of my favorite tools into action and see what happened.

First, I used a specific GPT to quickly research the company to gain insights into their business, strategy, product lines, how they make money and more.  

(comment 'Make it Happen' and I'll send it to you) 

Then I went into my favorite app Otter.ai, put all my previous discovery calls into a group so I could use their OtterPilot for Sales AI tool to ask pointed questions about my conversations and remember some key highlights. 

(comment 'Make it Happen' and I'll send you a link where you can download it for free.  Full disclosure, they're a sponsor of mine).

I then exported the information I got from the GPT and the transcripts from my conversations in Otter. 

I then went into Google's NotebookLM, uploaded all the documents and asked it to create a podcast for me on the topic. 

I downloaded the audio file of the 20 minute podcast it created for me to my iphone.

That entire process took me less than 10 minutes. 

I then listened to two people talk about everything I needed to know about the client on the drive down and was fully prepared for the conversation with the decision team.

It was absolutely bananas.

We're living in the future....

But what I will share is that in this group of women, we embrace chaos, we can do hard things, we have found/are finding our fire, we make it rain, and we are rebel souls.

Hello from sales-land at a PLG company üëã where boosting revenue through sales training demands more than just product know-how and basic sales skills. ü§î ü§î  Huh?  No really... here is what I am noticing...

Much of a sellers' success is about mastering those crucial "power skills."  From my experience, strategic Sales Enablement that incorporates building power skills into the training model is one key to helping sales teams deliver at the next level of success.

Why?

Because power skills (aka EQ, people skills, or "soft skills") can determine the quality of interactions -- internal and external -- and that is where a seller lives.  By balancing product training while honing these skills, we empower our reps to forge stronger connections with prospects and navigate the buying journey with finesse.

Investing in power skills pays off in tangible ways too. We see improved productivity and shorter sales cycles to name a few. When our reps excel in relationship-building and handling objections with emotional intelligence, we see a lift in both conversion rates and deal velocity, even in the trickier parts of the sales process. 

Said another way, including power skills in our Sales Enablement programs helps us to unlock even more potential in our teams, driving both revenue growth and the continued long-term success of our team. 

It doesn't have to be hard, either.  If you need some inspiration, check out my friend Jeff Riseley (Project Mamba) - who is bringing Performance Coaching to Sales, and changing the way we play the game, by helping leaders and reps prioritize these same Power Skills. üí™ 

Shout out to the brilliant Jon Selig as well, who is adding humor to power skills and helping reps deliver hyper-relevant messaging with extraordinary results!

To my fellow Sales Enablement enthusiasts, let's keep prioritizing power skills as we chart paths to new heights and increasing dollars!

data.text:
This past week, when I was üéº Training in Manila üé∂ (IYKYK), our team finalized an 8-week strategic sales enablement delivery that seamlessly combined #airSlate and #signNow product knowledge, sales skill acquisition, and a variety of practice opportunities.  I am proud to have leveraged the collective expertise of our GTM leadership team, showcasing our team's dedication to empowering new sales reps for unparalleled success. Here's a glimpse into the methodology, why it worked and the expected impact of how this effort ties to revenue.

1. Enabling sales reps requires building a deep understanding what they are selling. We delivered a comprehensive training on product features via real-life use cases, customer benefits and competitive differentiators. 

Why? 

Because when reps can confidently communicate with prospects, they can address buyer needs more effectively, articulate value more persuasively, and reap the benefits of increased conversion rates when they close more deals and generate more revenue.

2. Yet, as we know, Sales is as much about soft skills as it is about product knowledge.  Parallel to product training, we honed essential competencies including effective communication, active listening, objection handling, negotiation, and closing techniques. 

We are expecting improved sales productivity and shorter sales cycles due to reps' enhanced ability to build relationships, overcome objections, and gracefully guide prospects through their buying journey.

3. Practicing any skill creates excellence, and in sales, we know that fostering mastery through iterative enablement in a winning strategy. 

Our initiatives incorporated immersive practive avenues to reinforce both product knowledge and skill acquisition. This involved reps building their own ICP, role playing in simulated sales scenarios, dissecting real-life case studies, shadowing experienced reps, and engaging in continuous feedback sessions from a panel of coaches. 

By providing a safe environment for reps to courageously hone their abilities, we are already seeing tremendous growth in rep confidence and proficiency.  We know this will drive increased customer satisfaction and retention, as well as long-term revenue growth led by this team.

By strategically integrating product knowledge, skill acquisition, and practice, we not only equipped our newest cohort of sales reps for success, but have also set the stage for our team's most profitable year yet. This is not a conclusion post, but rather the beginning of a many-milestone journey for our team -- and I am eager to spearhead the next iteration of our plan as we move toward Q2.

More.

"We need more content"
"We need more sales plays"
"We need more product training"
"We need more enablement"

More, more, more. 

Every Enablement and Marketing team is absolutely exhausted as year end approaches and now they need to start planning for SKO and the other big plans their companies have for next year. 

Their backlog of enablement and content needs is probably longer than ever - as the pace of innovation and change only continues to accelerate.

Is the answer really "more"?

My hunch is that it's not more, it's better enablement.

One of my favorite quotes is this one by Henry Ford:

"If I had asked my customers what they wanted they would have said a faster horse." - Henry Ford

If you ask your sales teams what they need, their answer might be "more" because they can't even imagine a world of less and better.

It's not more content, instead it's better, faster access to the right content for your deals.

It's not more product training, it's better, shorter bite-sized trainings your reps can quickly consume in their moment of need.

It's not more process training, it's better more succinct process guidance that meets them in their workflow where they need it. 

Could you have MORE TIME back and MORE RESULTS if you shifted your focus to identifying what "better" enablement looks like for your organization?

Say goodbye to MORE in 2024, and HELLO to better.
